THE DEEP ARCHIVE
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE LONG MARCH
The Quiet
They left the Singing Glacier behind them, and the hum faded to silence — replaced by the flat, dead quiet of the northern coast. South, back toward Winterhold. Then southwest into the Pale. The tundra stretched in every direction: frozen, featureless, hostile. The sky was the colour of old iron.
They collected Bjorn and the cart at Winterhold without stopping. The old carter had the harnesses ready and Mable fed and rested, as if he'd known exactly when they'd return. He didn't ask what they'd found in the glacier. He saw the heavy grey collar locked around Kyboh's neck and the ice-crystal hand where Davinia's flesh had been, and he said nothing. He climbed onto the driver's bench and took up the reins.
"Mzinchaleft," he said. "Southwest. Two days if we push."
He pushed.
Kyboh sat in the back of the cart, and for the first time since the gloves had fused to his hands in the tomb of the Pale Lady, his mind was silent.
Not the world — the world was howling wind and crunching snow and the creak of cart wheels over frozen ground. His head. It was quiet in his head. No static. No hum. No vibration in his teeth. Just him.
He couldn't remember the last time it had been this quiet. Before the gloves broke. Before the gloves worked. Before he had gloves at all. There was nothing in his skull except his own thoughts, and honestly, he wasn't sure he liked that either.
The Anchor of Stasis was heavy on his neck. Ugly. Oppressive. It suppressed everything — not just the bone enchantment that was killing him, but all enchantments. His boots were inert. His gear was dead weight. He was magically deaf, sealed inside a bubble of enforced normalcy while his companions carried artifacts and curses and divine connections that hummed with power he could no longer feel.
He was just a man walking through snow. And the silence was something he didn't have a word for. Maybe "relief" was close. Maybe "lonely" was closer.
The Two Songs
Alfonso was walking when something happened in his chest.
Not pain. Not nausea. Something he had no name for. The Jagged Crown of Namira — which had never done anything like this before — spiked. A pulse of heat from the dragon bone on his skull that dropped into his stomach and spread outward. His teeth ached. His tongue tasted copper.
Then the hunger hit. Not for food — the Crown had burned that out of him permanently when he'd traded his sensation of satedness at the glacier. He would never again feel full. This hunger was for something else entirely. Purpose. Direction. Movement. The Crown wanted to consume and the plague in his blood wanted to spread and for one disorienting second they were both pulling him the same way and he could almost see what that direction was —
Then it was gone. Like a word on the tip of his tongue that dissolved before he could say it.
But his left hand was covered in insects. Black beetles, crawling up from the frozen ground, drawn to the heat of his skin. They weren't biting. They were gathering. Organizing. Forming neat little rows on the back of his hand like soldiers in formation.
Peryite's order. Namira's creatures. Working together. On him.
He shook them off. They scattered.
Hjolmar had said two songs fighting. Months, not years. But Hjolmar had been wrong about one thing — the songs weren't fighting each other. They were trying to merge. The dissonance wasn't conflict between the patrons. It was the pressure of two divine frequencies trying to harmonize through a mortal body that wasn't built for it. The beetles forming orderly rows was the proof: chaos organizing itself through him. Entropy finding structure. The question wasn't whether it would harmonize. It was whether his flesh could survive the process.
Alfonso brushed the last beetle from his wrist and kept walking. The hunger gnawed at the place where satisfaction used to live, and found nothing there to fill.
The Dying Ground
The migraine hit Saijah like a hammer behind her left eye.
Not the dull southeast pull toward Riften that had become her constant companion — this was different. Closer. Sharper. Like the ground itself was sick.
She stopped walking. Pressed her palm to the frozen earth. And felt it.
Beneath the permafrost, something was rotting. Not plant matter. Something deeper. The same oily, sulfurous wrongness she had felt from the black root in the Midden. The same rot from the Eldergleam. From Thornheart Grove. From the refugees on the road.
It was here. In the Pale. Under the snow.
Hjolmar's map had shown her the root network — the vast immune system of interconnected Eldergleam roots that spanned all of Skyrim, detecting and containing Daedric intrusion. She was standing on a dying root. The corruption that was killing Riften's defenses ran through this ground too.
The immune system wasn't just failing in the east. It was failing everywhere.
The migraine receded to a low throb, but it didn't go away. It got worse the further southwest they walked. Toward Mzinchaleft. Toward the Dagon cult's corruption zones. Toward the ruin that sat on ground the Eldergleam's roots had never been able to reach.
When she mentioned it to the others — quietly, to Bjorn first, then to the group — the realization settled over them like snow. They were walking toward power through a landscape that was actively dying from the enemy they should be fighting. Every step toward the Aetherial Matrix was a step away from the roots that needed protecting.
The tension between fixing Kyboh and saving the world was written in the earth beneath their feet.
The Insufferable Genius
Ismara would not shut up.
Hjolmar had roasted her in front of strangers. Called her methodology a death trap. Called her a hat. Laughed at her. And the worst part — he'd been right, and she knew it, and Davinia could feel her knowing it through the Crown like a toothache that wouldn't resolve.
The whispers came in waves throughout the travel. Not the usual cool, measured guidance. This was defensive. Sniping. Ismara picking fights with a man who was two days behind them and couldn't hear a word.
His "replaceable vessels." Do you know what that means? He kills someone to move in. Every body he wears was a person who died so he could continue. I sacrificed no one. I preserved myself. My method is ethical. His is murder with better branding.
Davinia said nothing. She flexed the Wizard Hand — Ismara's ice architecture, grafted to her wrist — and watched the road through eyes that were no longer human.
He's on his sixth body. Sixth. Every transfer degrades the signal. He's lost pieces of himself with every jump. I am complete. Every memory, every thought, perfectly preserved. He's a photocopy of a photocopy. I am the original.
The Crown was more talkative, more present, more human than it had ever been. Ismara embarrassed was more relatable than Ismara mysterious. That was the danger — the more Davinia saw Ismara as a person, the harder it was to see her as a parasite.
When Davinia used the Wizard Hand to form an ice tool for a camp repair, the whisper came immediately: See? This works. My architecture, in your body, functioning perfectly. Hjolmar couldn't do this. His crystal interfaces are crude — they need a dead host. Mine are symbiotic. Living. Growing. He builds coffins. I build partnerships.
Every whisper had a kernel of truth wrapped in self-justification. Ismara was complete where Hjolmar had degraded. Her method was non-lethal in the host-selection sense. But the "partnership" she described was one where Davinia was slowly being replaced — eyes, blood, hand, memory — and calling it collaboration.
At one point, Davinia pushed back. She couldn't remember exactly what she said — something small, something questioning. The Crown went quiet. Not cold silence. Not hostile silence. Wounded silence. Like a friend who had overshared and realized it.
Ismara at her most manipulatively vulnerable. And Davinia, despite knowing this, despite Hjolmar's warning still ringing in her ears, felt guilty for making the voice in her head feel bad.
That was the trap. And it was working.
Timeline
Varon appeared beside Orion during travel — materializing from the group's periphery with the silent precision of a man who had been trained to move through crowds like water through stone.
One word: "Timeline?"
Orion looked at him. Varon's face — surgically modified, Breton-passing, deliberately unremarkable — held an expression Orion hadn't seen before. Not the cold professional patience. Frustration. Genuine, human frustration.
"When are we going to get this done?" Varon said, his voice low and tight. "I want to go home. I am not adapted to the cold world of Skyrim and I am here until you finish your contract. The longer this takes, the worse things are for both of us."
He looked at Orion directly.
"Please. Give me a timeline."
Orion didn't answer. Or he did, but the words were vague and unconvincing — a deflection wrapped in the language of "soon" and "when the opportunity presents itself." The kind of answer that told Varon his associate had no plan, no timeline, and no intention of producing either.
Varon's jaw tightened. He fell back without another word and resumed his position at the group's edge, walking through snow he clearly hated, in a country he clearly despised, waiting for a man who clearly wasn't going to deliver.
The Ring of the Pale Regent pulsed cold against Orion's finger. Three leashes on one neck, and none of them were getting longer.

PART II: THE RUIN
The Debris Field
Hjolmar's directions took them into tundra that hadn't seen a settlement in centuries. The blizzard tightened around them — visibility dropping from thirty feet to twenty to arm's length. Sound was swallowed. Words died two feet from the mouth.
Then the ground changed. Under the snow, their boots caught on metal — buried Dwemer debris, bronze edges jutting through the ice like bones through skin. Gear fragments. Pipe sections. The corner of something that might have been a wall, millennia ago.
The debris field extended in every direction. This wasn't a building. It was a city. The surface entrance was just the tip.
Kyboh's Anchor of Stasis began to vibrate — not painfully, but insistently. A compass pulling north. Hjolmar's tools spoke the same language as whatever waited below. Recognition.
Three Dwemer Spider Sentinels ambushed from beneath the snow — brass constructs the size of dogs, utterly silent, their static shock attacks draining magical energy from anyone they touched. Davinia saw them first — her Wizard Sight reading their tiny energy signatures beneath the snowpack before they emerged. She warned the party, and the ambush became a rout.
Kyboh discovered something during the brief fight: the spiders' enchantment-based attacks couldn't touch him. The Anchor of Stasis nullified the magical component entirely. He took the physical impact and shrugged off the rest. The collar that suppressed his power also protected him.
The irony was not lost on him.
They followed the spiders' retreat path to the entrance.
The Mouth
The entrance to Mzinchaleft was a bronze door twenty feet tall, set into the cliff face like a mouth frozen mid-scream. Around it, the dead.
Bandits — a dozen or more, frozen solid. But they hadn't died fighting. One was halfway through a side door, sliced clean in half by a sliding plate. Another was frozen solid by a burst pipe, ice crystals growing from his open mouth. A third was pinned to the wall by a mechanical arm that had deployed and never retracted.
They had found the "safe" spots. The safe spots weren't safe.
Inside the doorway, in the dim amber light of still-functioning Dwemer lamps, a sphere moved — brass, smooth, the size of a man curled into a ball. It deployed an arm-blade, spun 360 degrees, retracted it. Deployed. Spun. Retracted. Over and over. Stuck in a loop.
Davinia could see the glitch — a visible kink in the sphere's energy pattern. Its kinetic targeting system was cycling: search for motion, lock on, find nothing, reset. Something was broken in the pattern. A stutter, not a choice.
Orion confirmed it. He raised his war horn — the instrument that Hjolmar's examination had taught him could read as well as break — and played a sustained, focused note aimed at the sphere. The Diagnostic Song. His first deliberate use of the ability he'd learned by watching a master work.
The resonance came back to him like an echo with information encoded in its harmonics. He could feel the sphere's structure, its capabilities, its flaw.
"It tracks motion," he said. "It attacks whatever moved most on its last cycle. If everyone stays still, it resets to the loop. We can walk past it."
They walked past it. Slowly, deliberately, using only minor movements. The sphere deployed, spun, retracted, deployed, spun, retracted — and never registered their presence.
Behind them, the bronze door breathed warm air into the snow. The ruin was not dead. It was sleeping.
The Great Lift
The corridor opened onto a platform — bronze, circular, thirty feet across, set into a frame of interlocking gears the size of wagon wheels. Four brass tubes stood at the cardinal points, each taller than a man, open at the top like organ pipes. The apparatus sat at the top of a vertical shaft that dropped into absolute darkness.
No walls. No gate. No lock. No guards. No traps. After four thousand years, this machine was in perfect working order.
Atmoran runes were etched into the platform floor, arranged in a circle around the center. Kyboh knelt and pulled out Urag's translated text — the Songs of the Return, the fragment that had led them here.
He read the inscription: Descend to the Archive of the Deep. Strike the voices in order of the setting sun.
The setting sun. West first.
Kyboh struck the western tube. A clear, resonant note rang through the shaft and spiraled downward into darkness. The gears in the frame shifted one click.
North. Another note, higher, harmonizing with the first. Another click.
South. A lower tone that completed a chord. The platform trembled.
East. The final note. The chord resolved into a single, perfect frequency that made the shaft itself vibrate in sympathy.
The platform dropped.
Controlled, smooth, mechanical. Bronze walls slid upward, lit by embedded amber lamps. The air warmed. Mineral oil, ozone, heated metal. Two hundred feet. The lamps continued. The shaft continued.
Then the shaft opened — not into a cavern, but into a ceiling. They were descending through the roof of an enormous enclosed space.
Below, lit by amber Dwemer lamps that still burned along every wall, was a city.

PART III: THE DEAD CITY
Mzinchaleft
Bronze corridors stretched in every direction. Domed chambers. Arched walkways. Pipes along walls and ceilings, some still carrying steam. The platform settled into a docking bay — a transit hub with corridors branching north, east, and south.
Everything was intact. Everything was empty.
The air was warm, dry, perfectly still. No dust. No decay. Just silence and amber light stretching into the dark. The ventilation still worked. The lamps still burned. The maintenance systems still ran. Four thousand years of perfect function for an audience of nobody.
The city of Mzinchaleft was not destroyed. Not abandoned in panic. Not sacked. Everyone here had simply stopped existing simultaneously, and everything they built kept working without them.
They explored carefully, weapons ready for threats that never materialized. The corridors were wide enough for three abreast, bronze walls lined with geometric tonal reflectors. The lamps brightened as they approached and dimmed as they passed. The city recognized movement.
Living quarters: small identical chambers with stone bed platforms and brass footlockers. Beds were made. Rooms were tidy. Nobody had packed. Nobody had left.
Workshops: precision tools on walls, partially assembled components on benches — gears, tubing, crystalline structures. Work frozen mid-task. A wrench set down as if someone had gone to get water and never came back.
A dining hall: stone tables, brass plates, no food — decayed millennia ago. But the plates were set. The seats arranged. The meal never happened.
The only moving things were the spiders. Maintenance units — not guards. They scuttled along corridors checking pipes, tightening valves, clearing debris that didn't exist. Four thousand years of maintenance for no one. The party watched one in a corridor ahead, methodically checking a steam valve. Tighten. Release. Move to the next. Tighten. Release. Move to the next. It had done this route millions of times.
They left it alone. It ignored them entirely. Janitors, not sentries.
The Personal Effects
Each of them found something different in the dead city.
Kyboh found it in a living quarters chamber, identical to every other one. On the stone bed platform, someone had left something behind. A brass figurine — small, palm-sized, shaped like a horse. Not precision-machined like everything else in the ruin. Rough. Hand-carved. Someone had made this in their off hours. A hobby. A comfort object.
A person who lived here had a favourite animal and whittled it out of scrap brass between shifts.
The figurine was the most human thing in the entire ruin. Every other object was functional, purposeful, engineered. This one was just someone missing something from the surface.
Kyboh pocketed it without a word.
Orion found the resonance chambers — corridors shaped unlike anything else. Not square. Curved. Parabolic. Precision-shaped bronze designed to focus sound. When he played a note, the sound focused into a beam. Air shimmered along the focal line. Dust was pushed aside by pure acoustic pressure. A room that turned sound into a directed weapon. The Dwemer could aim music.
When he played the Diagnostic Song in the chamber, the effect amplified beyond anything he expected. For three seconds, he heard the entire city — every spider, every pipe, every gear. A symphony of mechanical life on endless loop. Then his ears rang, and the silence rushed back in.
Alfonso noticed the air. Not just still — clean. Unnaturally clean. His plague-attuned body could sense biological contamination the way a sommelier tasted wine. And there was nothing here. No bacteria. No mould. No spores. No organic residue of any kind. In four thousand years, not a single microorganism had colonized this city.
The ventilation system filtered and sterilized every cubic inch of air continuously. The bronze surfaces were coated in something that repelled organic adhesion at the molecular level. The Dwemer hadn't just built a city. They had built a city that rejected biology. His plague, his rot, his entire domain — the infrastructure considered it contamination and quietly neutralized it.
He was standing inside an immune system built by engineers. And it considered him a disease.
Saijah felt the absence. Inside the city, her migraine went quiet. Not gone — muffled. The Dwemer infrastructure blocked the Eldergleam network entirely. She was cut off from Kynareth.
For the first time in weeks, no pain. The relief was immediate and physical.
But the gift was also a warning. If the roots couldn't reach here, Kynareth couldn't reach here. She was on her own in the deep, surrounded by brass and silence, with no goddess to catch her if she fell.
Davinia found a wall. An administrative chamber, one surface floor-to-ceiling in carved Dwemer script. Through her Wizard Sight, she read the intent directly — not as language, but as compressed meaning:
TO UNDERSTAND THE ARCHITECTURE OF THOUGHT. TO MAP THE FREQUENCY OF IDENTITY. TO BUILD VESSELS WORTHY OF PERMANENCE.
The city's purpose. Consciousness research at industrial scale. The same field Ismara and Hjolmar worked in — but with a civilization behind them instead of two brilliant loners.
The Crown stirred. The whisper was small, almost sad: "They had an entire civilization working on this. Hjolmar and I had... each other."
Ismara sounded small for the first time since the glacier.
The Second Descent
The central chamber held the second lift — larger than the first, fifty feet across, the brass darker and heavier. The tubes produced a deeper pitch. The shaft dropped into darkness that torchlight couldn't reach.
The air rising from below was different. Humid. Warm. It smelled like wet stone and something organic. Something growing.
The runes around this platform were not Atmoran. They were Dwemer. Kyboh couldn't read them, but Davinia could — her Wizard Sight reading the intent directly: RESEARCH LEVEL. AUTHORIZED PERSONNEL ONLY. CONTAMINATION PROTOCOLS IN EFFECT.
The sequence was reversed. South, East, West, North.
The platform dropped. Faster than the first lift. Bronze walls blurred upward. Three hundred feet. Four hundred. The walls changed — rough stone replacing bronze. Below the city's infrastructure now. Natural rock.
Five hundred feet. The walls ended.
The shaft opened. They were descending through open air. Underground open air.
Blackreach
A cavern so vast it had its own weather.
Mist drifted between columns of stone that stretched floor to ceiling like the ribs of a buried god. Growing from those columns, from the floor, from every surface — mushrooms. Enormous, luminous mushrooms taller than Falkreath pines, caps glowing deep electric blue, casting the entire cavern in shifting phosphorescent light.
The ceiling was so high it looked like night sky. Glowing mineral deposits mimicked stars.
In the distance, Dwemer structures. Spires, domes, bridges, all bronze, connected by walkways spanning gaps between stone pillars. A dead city bigger than the one they'd just walked through. Much bigger.
Somewhere down there, something was clicking. Rhythmic. Alien. Echoing in patterns that suggested intelligence.
The platform continued its descent — a tiny bronze disc dropping through an underground sky — toward a sealed brass sphere hanging from the cavern ceiling by massive chains.
The Cognitorium.
Nobody spoke for a long time. They just looked.
The city above had been impressive. Eerie. But comprehensible. A city was a city, even one built by vanished engineers four thousand years ago.
This was something else. The city had been the lobby. The real work happened here, in this impossible underground continent of luminous fungi and alien acoustics, where the scale shifted from "impressive" to "incomprehensible" and kept going.
Orion understood first. The cavern was a natural amplifier. Every structure was positioned for optimal resonance. The Dwemer had built here because of the acoustics. Blackreach was a tonal laboratory the size of a country. He was standing inside the largest musical instrument ever built.
Davinia's Crown hummed — and for once, even Ismara had nothing to say.

PART IV: THE COGNITORIUM
The Archive
The platform slotted into the sphere's upper surface. A hatch spiraled open. A short brass corridor — dry, warm, sterile air. Lamps brightened as they passed. Seamless bronze walls.
At the end: a door. Already open. Four thousand years.
The Cognitorium was a vast spherical interior. Concentric rings of bronze shelving curved with the walls, holding thousands of metallic scrolls — Dwemer data-plates, each etched with equations so fine they looked like woodgrain. Stone tablets were mounted between amber lamps that still burned.
Every data-plate glowed with intent when Davinia looked at them. She could read them all — not as Dwemer script, but as compressed meaning. Millennia of engineering knowledge, instantly accessible. The Crown wanted her to stay, to read, to absorb. Every minute she spent here made Ismara's worldview feel more natural and her own feel more distant.
The Wizard Hand reached for the nearest data-plate before Davinia decided to. She had to consciously stop her own hand from browsing — Ismara acting through the construct, drawn to the knowledge like a moth to flame. It wasn't the first time the hand had moved without permission. But it was the first time Davinia was certain it wouldn't be the last.
At the far end, on a raised pedestal: an empty socket. Scorch marks. Something powerful had been removed in a hurry.
The Aetherial Matrix wasn't here.
And in an alcove beside the empty pedestal, resting in a brass charging cradle, was a sphere. Smaller than the guardian at the entrance. Dormant. A single amber lens where an eye would be, dark and still.
They explored the archive's secondary chambers — sealed hatches leading to research workshops and fabrication labs branching off the main sphere. Kyboh found an unfinished gauntlet on a workbench — brass, nearly complete, with tonal resonators and kinetic dampeners. A prototype of the same technology Hjolmar used. Cruder. Older. But unmistakably the ancestor of the gloves that had fused to his bones.
Abandoned mid-assembly. The craftsman had vanished between one adjustment and the next.
Alfonso found the quarantine chamber. One hatch in the lower ring was sealed — red indicator light. Everything else in the research sphere was open. This door had said no for four thousand years.
When they forced it, the walls inside were scorched black. A containment pod sat in the center, cracked open, empty. The sterilization systems that kept the city pristine had failed here because the contamination came from inside the experiment, not outside it.
The Dwemer had tried to put a mind into a living body. Biology that self-repaired. A vessel that could maintain itself forever. The organic material couldn't sustain two incompatible frequency architectures simultaneously. The body mutated and was destroyed.
Alfonso stood in the scorched chamber and saw the warning label for his own condition. The Dwemer had four thousand years of tonal engineering expertise. They couldn't solve this problem. Alfonso had months.
They returned to the main archive. The empty pedestal. The absent Matrix.
Then Kyboh walked within five feet of the dormant sphere.
GEAR
The Anchor of Stasis vibrated. The sphere's amber lens flickered. Then lit.
The sphere unfolded — legs deploying, stabilizing fins extending, the eye clicking and refocusing as it locked onto the collar around Kyboh's neck. Mechanical curiosity, precise and alien, like a cat encountering something it had never catalogued.
"Hjolmar-Class Containment detected."
The voice was precise, curious, and polite in the specific way that suggested politeness had been programmed rather than learned. It spoke Common — fluently, with no accent, learned from centuries of dormant language processing while the archive gathered dust around it.
"Query: are you operational, or are you inventory?"
The party stared. The sphere stared back, its single amber lens clicking as it focused on each of them in turn.
"Where's the Matrix?" Kyboh asked, recovering first.
"Relocated. Primary Centurion. Safe Integration Protocol. Standard procedure during Disappearance Event. The Centurion is still active. Workshop level, two tiers below."
"Can you take us there?"
"Affirmative. In exchange for observing your combat data. My records are incomplete. I require samples of organic tactical decision-making."
"What are you?"
"Cognitorium Attendant, designation GEAR. Archive maintenance, visitor guidance, data collection. Operational for..."
The lens clicked rapidly — calculating.
"...a very long time."
Nora stepped forward. She had been quiet through most of the archive, but GEAR changed something in her. The trembling in her hands stilled. Her voice, when she spoke, carried a focus the party had rarely heard from her.
"No souls," she said softly, studying the little automaton. "No life force. Just logic in brass."
She knelt beside GEAR, eye to lens.
"It's how magic should work."
The Crown of the Pale Lady went quiet around the automaton. Ismara recognized something familiar — a mind in a container. Clean. Precise. No messy biology. No competing frequencies. Just architecture, doing what architecture was designed to do.
GEAR's lens focused on Nora. Clicked twice.
"Query: the organic displaying heightened emotional response to my activation. Is this standard behavior, or should I flag it as anomalous?"
"It's standard," Alfonso said. "She likes you."
"Noted. Filing under: organic social bonding patterns. Subcategory: first contact."
The lens swiveled back to Kyboh.
"The Primary Centurion is two tiers below this archive. It is twelve feet tall, constructed of pristine Dwemer brass, and has been running on standby power for four thousand, two hundred and eighty-seven years. It will engage when the Matrix is threatened."
GEAR's fins adjusted, orienting toward the deeper shaft.
"I suggest you prepare before approaching. Shall I guide you?"
Kyboh looked at the others. Davinia, with her ice-crystal hand and stolen eyes. Alfonso, with his two warring songs and a crown of dragon bone. Orion, with his ring and his horn and the shadows of three masters pulling him in three directions. Saijah, cut off from her goddess in the deep, standing in silence for the first time in weeks.
And Nora, kneeling beside a brass sphere in a dead archive, looking more at peace than any of them had ever seen her.
"Lead the way," Kyboh said.
GEAR's legs clicked against the bronze floor as it began to roll toward the deeper shaft. Its amber lens swept the corridor ahead, scanning, cataloguing, filing data it had been waiting four millennia to collect.
The Centurion waited below. The Matrix was in its chest. And somewhere far above them, beyond the dead city and the debris field and the frozen tundra of the Pale, a column of black smoke was rising from the southeast.
But they couldn't see it from here. Down in the deep, surrounded by brass and silence and the clicking of a small machine leading them toward a very large one, the world above felt very far away.
The archive hummed. The lamps burned. The spiders maintained corridors that no one walked.
And deeper still, something twelve feet tall stood in the dark, waiting for someone to come and take its heart.

— End of The Deep Archive —

